<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1375,1726]" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,287,1375,1401]" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Comments.</emphasis>
This group was proposed in a recent monograph on the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blanchard" authorityYear="1845" box="[935,1097,1375,1401]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="240" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Gryllacrididae</taxonomicName>
classification (
<bibRefCitation author="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J." pageId="1" pageNumber="240" pagination="1 - 100" refId="ref4200" refString="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J. (2019) A proposal towards classification of the Raspy Crickets (Orthoptera: Stenopelmatoidea: Gryllacrididae) with zoogeographical comments: An initial contribution to the higher classification of the Gryllacridines. Zootaxa, 4605 (1), 1 - 100. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4605.1.1" type="journal article" year="2019">Cadena-Castañeda, 2019</bibRefCitation>
). It is characterized by a blackish or reddish head, a very well-developed median ocellus (
<figureCitation box="[1296,1383,1411,1437]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1699,1723]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1673]" captionTargetId="figure-22@2.[151,1436,179,1673]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Triaenogryllacris triaena. Male holotype (yellowish form). A. Habitus in dorsal view. B. Frons. C-D. Terminalia in lateral and ventral views respectively. Photos: M. Paris (MNCN)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381686" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381686/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1397,1432,1411,1437]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[175,1408,193,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-22@6.[166,1422,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Triaenogryllacris diaena n.sp. A-B. Habitus in lateral and dorsal views respectively. C. Head and thorax in lateral view. D. Frons." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381698" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381698/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">4C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,189,1447,1474]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[161,1428,249,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-44@9.[151,1436,236,1920]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 6. Triaenogryllacris horaciotrianai n. sp. female. A. Frons. B-C. Head and thorax in lateral and dorsal view respectively. D-E. Terminalia in lateral and ventral view. F. Ovipositor apex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381712/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">6A</figureCitation>
), the subgenital plate of the male without styles and with two or three medium-sized sharp processes (
<figureCitation box="[1342,1431,1447,1473]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1699,1723]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1673]" captionTargetId="figure-22@2.[151,1436,179,1673]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Triaenogryllacris triaena. Male holotype (yellowish form). A. Habitus in dorsal view. B. Frons. C-D. Terminalia in lateral and ventral views respectively. Photos: M. Paris (MNCN)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381686" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381686/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,188,1483,1510]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[178,1412,193,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-21@7.[168,1420,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Triaenogryllacris species, male terminalia. A-E. Triaenogryllacris diaena n. sp. F. Triaenogryllacris triaena. A-B. Terminalia in axial view, photo and draw respectively. C-D. Terminalia in lateral and ventral view. E-F. Subgenital plate." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381706/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">5D</figureCitation>
), and the females with a pair of papillae on each side of the last abdominal sternite (
<figureCitation box="[1147,1215,1483,1510]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[161,1428,249,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-44@9.[151,1436,236,1920]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 6. Triaenogryllacris horaciotrianai n. sp. female. A. Frons. B-C. Head and thorax in lateral and dorsal view respectively. D-E. Terminalia in lateral and ventral view. F. Ovipositor apex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381712/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
D-E). 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Triaenogryllacrae</emphasis>
is represented by the monotypic genus, 
<emphasis box="[687,890,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Karny" authorityYear="1937" box="[687,886,1519,1545]" class="Insecta" family="Haglidae" genus="Triaenogryllacris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="240" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Triaenogryllacris</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and the new species described in this paper, all from Colombian and Ecuadorian Andes (
<figureCitation box="[616,690,1555,1581]" captionStart="MAP 1" captionStartId="8.[151,209,1636,1660]" captionTargetBox="[157,1428,711,1604]" captionTargetId="figure-219@8.[151,1436,705,1613]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="MAP 1. Triaenogryllacris distribution. Including the pink, yellow and green forms of T. triaena." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4386518" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4386518/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Map 1</figureCitation>
). The 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[767,846,1555,1581]" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Group</emphasis>
is distinguished from the other American genera by the tegmen venation corresponding to 
<typeStatus box="[583,639,1592,1618]" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Type</typeStatus>
IV (
<emphasis box="[692,754,1592,1617]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Karny, H. H." box="[762,902,1591,1618]" pageId="1" pageNumber="240" pagination="19 - 105" refId="ref4465" refString="Karny, H. H. (1924) Beitrage zur malayischen Orthopterenfauna VI. Die Gryllacriden des Buitenzorger Museums. Treubia, 5 (1 - 3), 19 - 105. https: // doi. org / 10.14203 / treubia. v 5 i 1 - 3.1681" type="journal article" year="1924">Karny, 1924</bibRefCitation>
) and the strange hindwing venation. The males do not have styli, as in the genera of 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[559,724,1627,1653]" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Hyperbaenini</emphasis>
. This character is interpreted as convergence, since both groups are found in different subfamilies, and are separated by many other characters such as the shape of the hind femur tegmina, and pattern of wing venation (
<bibRefCitation author="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J." box="[592,877,1699,1725]" pageId="1" pageNumber="240" pagination="1 - 100" refId="ref4200" refString="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J. (2019) A proposal towards classification of the Raspy Crickets (Orthoptera: Stenopelmatoidea: Gryllacrididae) with zoogeographical comments: An initial contribution to the higher classification of the Gryllacridines. Zootaxa, 4605 (1), 1 - 100. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4605.1.1" type="journal article" year="2019">Cadena-Castañeda, 2019</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
